cs.PL, cs.SE, cs.AR, cs.CR, cs.DC. 

The paper discusses the design and implementation of a tool that uses transactional memory to reduce the latency of symbolic-execution applications. This involves techniques for checking whether values are symbolic and the use of hardware-supported transactional memory. Based on this, the most likely sub-category is cs.PL (Programming Languages) as the paper discusses the design and implementation of a tool. The next likely sub-category is cs.SE (Software Engineering) as the paper discusses methods to verify the behavior of a client in a client-server application. The paper also discusses techniques for reducing the cost of checking whether values are symbolic, which could fall under cs.AR (Architecture) or cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). Finally, the use of hardware-supported transactional memory could fall under cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing).
